{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 03:15:22.923918", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nSummary of network health\n- Overall OSPF domain is functioning for most areas: many subnets (e.g., 10.1.2.0/24, 10.2.x.0/24) successfully reach server farm endpoints; RTTs and reachability are normal.\n- DNS server is up and listening on 10.200.0.2:53, and hosts outside 10.1.1.0/24 can resolve and access web services via web99.local (load balancer).\n- The segment 10.1.1.0/24 is isolated from the rest of the network.\n\nObserved anomalies\n1) End-user impact on 10.1.1.0/24\n- host_1_1_1_1 (10.1.1.18/24, GW 10.1.1.1) cannot reach anything beyond its subnet:\n  - Ping to dns_server (10.200.0.2) fails with “Network is unreachable.”\n  - HTTP requests to web99.local and web0.local time out (~5s total each attempt).\n  - resolv.conf points to nameserver 10.200.0.2, but DNS isn’t reachable due to routing isolation.\n\n- In contrast, host_2_1_1_1 (10.2.1.19/24) can:\n  - Ping dns_server successfully (0% loss, ~3 ms RTT).\n  - Resolve and reach web99.local with normal timings (~1.1 s total), confirming the rest of the network path (including DNS and load balancer) is healthy.\n\n2) Distribution router for 10.1.1.0/24 is not participating in OSPF\n- router_dist_1_1 (GW 10.1.1.1, core-facing 172.16.0.7/31) shows FRR active but no OSPF neighbors, no learned routes:\n  - show ip ospf neighbor: no neighbors.\n  - show ip route: only connected routes (10.1.1.0/24 on br0 and 172.16.0.6/31 on eth0); no OSPF routes present.\n  - frr running-config: router ospf has only router-id set; there are no network statements/area assignments (“Number of areas attached to this router: 0”).\n\n- Router cannot reach server networks:\n  - Ping from router_dist_1_1 to dns_server: “Network is unreachable.”\n\n3) Control comparison with another distribution router\n- router_dist_2_1 is healthy:\n  - OSPF neighbor with core present.\n  - OSPF-learned routes include 10.200.0.0/24 and multiple 10.1.x/10.2.x/172.16.x prefixes.\n  - Hosts behind this router (e.g., host_2_1_1_1) exhibit normal end-to-end service behavior.\n\nLocalization of the fault\n- Fault localized to router_dist_1_1 (distribution layer for 10.1.1.0/24):\n  - It is the first L3 hop from host_1_1_1_1 (default gateway).\n  - It lacks OSPF adjacencies and OSPF-learned routes to the rest of the fabric.\n  - As a result, it cannot forward traffic to server networks (10.200.0.0/24) or other areas.\n\nRoot cause\n- Misconfiguration of OSPF on router_dist_1_1:\n  - FRR is running but the OSPF process has no areas/networks configured. No network/area statements are present, resulting in zero OSPF neighbors and no route exchange with the core.\n  - This isolates the 10.1.1.0/24 subnet from the rest of the OSPF domain, causing “Network is unreachable” for off-subnet traffic and preventing DNS and web access for hosts in that subnet.\n\nKey evidence\n- host_1_1_1_1: default route via 10.1.1.1 present; ping to 10.200.0.2 fails “Network is unreachable.”\n- router_dist_1_1:\n  - ifconfig/ip addr: br0 10.1.1.1/24; core-facing 172.16.0.7/31 up.\n  - frr status: active.\n  - show running-config: router ospf with only router-id; no network/area configuration.\n  - show ip ospf neighbor: none.\n  - show ip route: only connected prefixes; no OSPF routes.\n  - ping to dns_server: “Network is unreachable.”\n- router_dist_2_1 (good comparator):\n  - Has OSPF neighbor(s) and OSPF-learned routes including 10.200.0.0/24.\n  - Hosts behind it can reach DNS and web services.\n\nImpact assessment\n- All hosts in 10.1.1.0/24 are unable to reach DNS or the server farm (10.200.0.0/24), breaking name resolution and access to web services (including the load balancer web99.local).\n- Other areas/subnets are unaffected and operating normally.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 48025, "output_tokens": 4508, "total_tokens": 52533, "in